<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-228-902  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 228 902.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  March 12 1990 v7 n11 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>EC convinces PTTs to drop price scheme. (European Commission; PostTelephone and Telegraph)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crockett, Barton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The European Commission has convinced 26 European carriers to giveup an international circuit price-setting routine that may haveled to steep surcharges and overcharging.andP;  Prices for privatelines in Europe may drop drastically.andP;  The decision should benefitusers enormously.andP;  In 1989, international private-line rates werepriced four to 20 times above cost.andP;  Ovum Ltd figured the costs ofan international leased line at about $2,200 per year, however theEuropean carriers charge between $11,000 and $42,000 for thecircuits.andP;  One reason lines are so expensive is that nationalcarriers set prices through joint agreements such as the GeneralPrinciples for international leased circuits.andP;  Tariffs areunlikely to change quickly.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     European Community. Commission of the European CommunitiesTelecommunicationsPricing PolicyInternational CommunicationsPrice IncreasesCommunications Service Suppliers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>